<seg id=1> A Majority of Hongkong Residents Unwilling to Claim Themselves Chinese </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP, Hongkong) According to a poll announced yesterday, despite Hongkong's return to China last year, a majority of Hongkong residents are unwilling to claim themselves Chinese. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> As revealed in the poll, 40% of 6.5 million Hongkong residents call themselves "Hongkongese", 22.3% call themselves "Hongkong Chinese", 20.6% call themselves "Chinese residing in Hongkong". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The poll was conducted by the Social Sciences Research Center of University of Hongkong. </seg>
<seg id=5> Only 20.6% among the 517 interviewees claimed themselves Chinese, 1.6% gave no clear answer or made no comment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In a similar survey conducted half a year after Hongkong's return to China, 35.9% called themselves "Hongkongese", 18% claimed themselves Chinese. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> 15 months have passed since Hongkong returned to China, Hongkong Government has been trying to remind its residents that they are Chinese. </seg>
<seg id=8> Some Hongkong officials complained that over 150 years of colonization by Great Britain has made it difficult for Hongkong residents to claim their identities. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The day before yesterday, Special Administrative Region (SAR) Chief Executive Tung Cheehwa said in his National Day address that "as a Chinese, I feel greatly honored, and I'm very proud of the development of our country". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> To foster a sense of Chinese citizens among Hongkong residents, Hongkong Civil Education Promotion Committee compiled and published a book called "I'm a Chinese", which is excellent both in pictures and words. </seg>
</p>
